'''St Mary's Church, Stainburn''', is a [[redundant church|redundant]] [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] church in the village of [[Stainburn]], [[North Yorkshire]], England ({{gbmapping|SE247485}}).  It has been designated by [[English Heritage]] as a Grade&nbsp;I [[listed building]],<ref name=hg>{{Citation |url= http://www.heritagegateway.org.uk/Gateway/Results_Single.aspx?uid=330565&resourceID=5 |title= ''St Mary, Stainburn'' |publisher= |year=2006|work=Heritage Gateway website | accessdate= 10&nbsp;August 2010}}</ref> and is under the care of the [[Churches Conservation Trust]].<ref name=cct>{{Citation | url = http://www.visitchurches.org.uk/findachurch/st-mary-stainburn/?region=North_Yorkshire&offset=1 | | title = St Mary, Stainburn | accessdate = 10&nbsp;August 2010| publisher = [[Churches Conservation Trust]]}}</ref>

==History==

The church was built in the 12th&nbsp;century as a [[chapel of ease]] in the [[parish]] of [[Kirkby Overblow]].<ref name=be>{{Citation | url = http://www.britainexpress.com/attractions.htm?attraction=4235| title = Stainburn, St Mary's Church| accessdate = 10&nbsp;August 2010| publisher = Britain Express}}</ref>  Alterations were made to the church in the 17th&nbsp;century. In 1894 it was restored and additions were made by [[C. Hodgson Fowler|C.&nbsp;Hodgson Fowler]].  This included re-roofing the church, refitting the chancel, the addition of the [[vestry]], and relaying of the grave slabs.<ref name=hg/>  

==Architecture==
===Exterior===
St Mary's is constructed in [[gritstone]] [[rubble]] and has a graduated stone slate roof.  Its plan consists of a three-[[bay (architecture)|bay]] [[nave]] with a south porch, and a single-bay [[chancel]] with a north vestry. A two-arched [[bellcote]] stands on the junction between the nave and the chancel.<ref name=hg/>  Much of the church is [[Norman architecture|Norman]] in style.<ref name=be/>  The porch has a round-arched doorway, and the door to the church has a plain [[Tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]].  To the left of the door is a square-headed window and to the right are two [[lancet window]]s on each side of a window with a pointed arch.  At the west end is a lancet window, and in the north wall is a two-light [[mullion]]ed window.  The chancel is lower and narrower than the nave.  The east window has three lights and is in [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular]] style.  On the south wall of the chancel is a blocked doorway and a three-light mullioned window.<ref name=hg/>  

===Interior===
The chancel arch is Norman in style, having a round arch and two orders.  The [[baptismal font|font]] is Norman and consists of a circular carved bowl on a circular stem.  The pews date from the 16th and 17th&nbsp;centuries.

